        },
        {
          "number": 4,
          "slidetitle": "Data Poisoning and Model Manipulation",
          "subtitle": "Corrupting the Data AI Systems Trust",
          "slidecontent": "• Attackers secretly inject false or misleading data into the datasets used to train AI systems\n• This corrupts how the AI learns, causing it to make wrong or harmful decisions\n• Subtle and hard to detect\n• A public sector example: manipulated training data could cause a fraud detection system to approve fraudulent claims\n• Poisoning can happen during initial training or when a system updates itself with new data\n• Even small amounts of corrupted data can significantly skew an AI system's outputs over time"
        },
        {
          "number": 5,
          "slidetitle": "Securing AI Against Insider Threats",
          "subtitle": "Recognising Risks From Within Your Organisation",
          "slidecontent": "• Staff with legitimate access can misuse or leak sensitive AI training data\n• Disgruntled employees, contractors, and third-party vendors all pose insider risk\n• Privilege creep (accumulating unnecessary access over time) quietly increases exposure\n• Monitor unusual query patterns or bulk data exports from AI systems\n• Limit who can retrain, update, or interact directly with AI models\n• Regular access reviews help catch risks before damage occurs"
        },
        {
          "number": 6,
          "slidetitle": "Defending Against Adversarial Attacks",
          "subtitle": "Strengthening AI resilience against manipulation attempts",
          "slidecontent": "• Adversarial attacks trick AI systems by feeding them subtly altered inputs designed to cause errors or unsafe outputs\n• Common in image recognition, fraud detection, and automated decision tools used across public services\n• Input validation and anomaly detection help catch suspicious data before it reaches the model\n• Regular stress-testing against known attack patterns\n• Keeping training data clean and well-governed reduces the risk of manipulation taking hold\n• Human oversight at critical decision points adds a vital layer of defence"
        },
        {
          "number": 7,
          "slidetitle": "Strengthening AI Security Posture",
          "subtitle": "Building resilience across AI security layers",
          "slidecontent": "• Regular security audits tailored specifically to AI components and data pipelines\n• Staff training on recognising unusual AI behaviour\n• Layered access controls limiting who can query, modify, or retrain AI systems\n• Incident response plans updated to cover AI-specific failure scenarios\n• Continuous monitoring of model outputs for signs of manipulation or drift\n• Collaboration with national cyber agencies to stay current on emerging AI threats"
        },
